        <abstract> 
<p>Believes species have arisen, like domestic varieties, with much extinction, and that there are no such things as independently created species. Explains why he believes species of the same genus <hi rend="italic">generally</hi> have a common or continuous area; they are actual lineal descendants.</p> 
            <p>Discusses fertilisation in the bud and the insect pollination of papilionaceous flowers. His theory explains why, despite the risk of injury, cross-fertilisation is usual in the animal and vegetable kingdoms, even in hermaphrodites.</p>
        </abstract>
